<TITLE> Explosion hits Sri Lanka opposition financier's home </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 COLOMBO, Jan 22(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - An explosion hit the home of a financier of opposition presidential candidate General Sarath Fonseka on Friday, amid increasing violence before a close presidential election next week. Tiran Alles, a wealthy businessman who split from President Mahinda Rajapaksa after supporting him in the 2005 election, said no one was hurt in the blast. "There was an explosion at my house. Somebody threw a bomb, and part of my house was burnt and my car is in ashes," Alles told Reuters. Police said they were investigating, but had no suspects. Four people have been killed already in attacks leading up to the Tuesday's presidential vote, in which Rajapaksa has seen his seemingly insuperable popularity fade with Fonseka's entry into the race. Fonseka led the army to victory over the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) in May, and he launched his campaign with a motley coalition of political parties backing him for the sole purpose of defeating Rajapaksa. The president and his former army commander fell out, with Fonseka accusing Rajapaksa of unjustly sidelining him over unfounded coup fears. The government has said that it expected Fonseka's campaign to carry out some kind of staged attack to garner sympathy for his campai
